<DIV1>
<P><PB REF="1">
THE <HI>IVDGMENT-DAY,</HI> A POEM.</P>
<P>BY <HI>AARON HILL,</HI> <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR></P>
<P><HI>LONDON:</HI> Printed for <HI>T.</HI> JAUNCY, at the <HI>Angel</HI> without <HI>Temple-Bar.</HI> Price One Shilling.</P>
<P>Where may be had (ju&s;t Publi&s;hed) <HI>An Ode on the Power of Mu&s;ick,</HI> by Mr. <HI>Mi$chell.</HI> (Price One Shilling.)</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="preface">
<PB N="1" REF="2">
<HEAD>THE PREFACE.</HEAD>
<P>_A MAN, who con&s;iders Flattery with the &s;harpe&s;t Con|tempt, will be, &s;ometimes, <HI>provok'd,</HI> by the &s;udden &s;hi|ning out of an <HI>irre&s;i&s;tible</HI> Virtue, to give vent to his Admiration in a Publick Acknowledgement. Thus the Monument, in <HI>We&s;tmin&s;ter Abbey,</HI> which His Grace, the Duke of <HI>Buckingham</HI> erected lately to the Memory of Mr. <HI>Dryden,</HI> is &s;uch a Mark of Publick Spirit, as entitled him to the general Thanks of his Country; and demands that his late, lamented Death &s;hould be con|&s;idered as one of the greate&s;t Calamities, which could have befallen Men of Let|ters. It is a mor$tfying Reflection to me. that I find my&s;elf prevented in the Re&s;olution I had $orm'd, to have dedicated to that <HI>truly Noble</HI> Duke, the following <HI>POEM,</HI> that I might, by that Means, have found Occa&s;ion to expre&s;s the ju&s;t Sentiments which I feel, and which I hope, all his Countrymen feel, when they con&s;ider this Action. It was a Noble Extent of his Protection, to the <HI>A&s;hes</HI> of a great Man, who&s;e <HI>Life</HI> too was embeli&s;h'd, by the Honour of his Patronage. To di&s;tingui&s;h him thus, more than <HI>others</HI> have di&s;tingui&s;h'd him, de&s;erves to pa&s;s as a Proof, that he al&s;o better under&s;tood him. We have ma|ny, I believe, who wanted not <HI>Genero&s;ity,</HI> to have <HI>prevented</HI> the Duke of <HI>Buckingham,</HI> in this fine Act of his Bounty: And, that they <HI>did</HI> it <HI>not,</HI> may, therefore fairly, be &s;uppo&s;ed owing to their fainter <HI>Ta&s;te</HI> of his Excellence.</P>
<P>Yet, while I join with the World, to prai&s;e and admire the Duke's &s;o gene|rous Exertion of his Concern, for the Honour of an excellent Poet's Memory, I feel my&s;elf drawn a&s;ide by the force of a Reflection, very different in its Na|ture. A Reflection which obliges me to lament the ill Fate, and Unfruitful|ne&s;s of an Art, of acknowledged Benefit, and Delight to Mankind: But which,
<PB N="2" REF="3">
notwith&s;tanding its Importance, expo&s;es even the <HI>Be&s;t</HI> of its Profe&s;&s;ors, to a Life of $Word$ and Neglect; and to a Death, &s;o <HI>ob&s;cure,</HI> that they depend but on the ca&s;ual Humanity of &s;ome <HI>Patron,</HI> for the Di&s;tinction of a <HI>Tomb|&s;tone.</HI> The Moral U&s;e which I would wi&s;h to be made from this Ob&s;ervation, is&mdash;That <HI>Poetry,</HI> a graceful <HI>Exerci&s;e,</HI> is a very airy <HI>Bu&s;ine&s;s.</HI> It produces, I know not what, of a &s;hadowy Satisfaction, which unbends us from the Reli&s;h of more profitable Application! A kind of Barren <HI>&s;well</HI> of Fancy, which ma&s;tes our Prime of Strength, in a Whirlwind of Imagination; and, then flattens $n us maliciou&s;ly, in that helple&s;s Stage of Life, when we are no lon|ger <HI>fit</HI> for <HI>Action;</HI> And, when Wi&s;dom &s;erves for nothing, but to reproach as with a Folly, which is now become pa&s;t Remedy.</P>
<P>A Man, who expects to be the Maker of his own Fortune, and chu&s;es <HI>Poe|try,</HI> for the Means he will proceed by, mu&s;t reduce him&s;elf to a Conde&s;cention of exchanging his own Will, for a pliable Adherence to every Body's, who can benefit him. His Rea&s;on is to be <HI>bow'd,</HI> till it <HI>buckles clo&s;e</HI> to the Times he lives in; and it will not be 'what is <HI>worthy,</HI> that gives Aim to his Fancy, but what is <HI>taking</HI> and <HI>fa&s;hionable.</HI></P>
<P>Mr. <HI>Dryden</HI> had a Genius, that was capable of carrying him, a great Way beyond the highe&s;t of tho&s;e wonderful Flights he made. He had a Soul too, which, had it been left to the natural Freedom of its Choice, would have di&s;|dain'd &s;ome little Flatteries, which have been peevi&s;hly remark'd, in his Be|haviour, and his Writings. But $e ow'd to his dependent Condition of Life, the unhappy Nece&s;&s;ity of being in&s;pir'd by his <HI>Wants,</HI> and making a Mu&s;e of his Mi&s;ery. Or, rather, he ow'd that Condition to his not early enough di&s;|cerning, that <HI>Poetry,</HI> however fit to be the <HI>&s;hine,</HI> is too thin for the <HI>Sub&s;tance</HI> of a Wi&s;e Man's Application. It is like <HI>Jewels,</HI> and <HI>Embroidery,</HI> which &s;erve to glitter &s;plendidly, on a warm Dre&s;s, worn under them; but would draw on <HI>Deri&s;ion,</HI> in&s;tead of <HI>Regard,</HI> were they hung about the <HI>Naked.</HI> What Imported it <HI>Shake&s;pear, Spencer, Cowley, Dryden,</HI> and &s;ome others, that their Imagination was clear and lively? Their Judgment &s;trong and &s;olid? and thei$ Memory di|&s;tinct and tenacious? Their <HI>Syren Mu&s;es</HI> &s;uck'd 'em <HI>in,</HI> and they were en|gulph'd among Quick&s;ands. They were unwilling, at fir&s;t, and, by Degrees, be|came <HI>unable,</HI> to con&s;ider Fortune as a richer Game than Fancy. What <HI>One</HI> of them reproach'd his Mu&s;e for, might have been &s;aid by them <HI>All:</HI> And will, hereafter be complain'd of, by a Thou&s;and of their Followers.</P>
<Q><L>To all the Po&s;ts of Honour, and of Gain,</L>
<L>I often &s;teer my Cour&s;e in vain:</L>
<L>Thy Gale comes cro&s;s, and drives me back again!</L>
<L>Thou &s;lacken'&s;t all my Nerves of Indu&s;try,</L>
<L>By forcing them, &s;o oft, to be</L>
<L>The tinkling Strings of thy loo&s;e Min&s;trel&s;ie.</L>
<P>COWLEY.</P></Q>
<P><PB N="3" REF="4">
When Poetry &s;hall be adopted a Daughter of the <HI>State,</HI> and a Publick Dow|ry allotted her, becoming her Charms, and her Dignity, all the Lands of the Mu&s;es will be carefully Cultivated. <HI>Skillful</HI> Gardiners will find it worth their whole Study, to make Improvements in her Wilderne&s;s: And her <HI>Weeds</HI> being pluck'd up, will give Place to <HI>Plants</HI> of <HI>Profit.</HI> Till then, it is the Duty of every Man, who has e&s;cap'd Shipwreck, him&s;elf, to &s;et up a <HI>Mark,</HI> that may warn <HI>other Coa&s;ters.</HI></P>
<P>I undertook to write this <HI>Poem</HI> at the Reque&s;t of Mr. <HI>Jo&s;eph Mitchell,</HI> a young Gentleman of <HI>Edinburgh,</HI> who&s;e late admirable Attempts in <HI>Poetry,</HI> make it needle&s;s to tell the World, what they are to hope from his great Genius. I am not a little &s;orry that the unhappy Death above mentioned, has prevented me in a De&s;ign I had form'd, to have pointed out his <HI>Merit,</HI> to the Ob&s;ervation of that Noble Patron, who would have taken equal Plea&s;ure in di&s;covering and encoura|ging it. The Duke of <HI>Buckingham</HI> &s;tood in the Front of tho&s;e ten or twelve great Judges, which a <HI>Poet;</HI> who is ambitious of beginning to be generally under&s;tood, about a Hundred Years hence, would have had in his View to plea&s;e at pre&s;ent.</P>
<P>To trouble the Reader with but a Word or two of the <HI>Poem,</HI> Its Subject has been frequently attempted of late, but I am very much mi&s;taken, or, it has been con&s;idered too narrowly. In the <HI>Creation,</HI> indeed, I confin'd my&s;elf to <HI>Mo|&s;es</HI>'s Account of it; and, for that Rea&s;on only, de&s;crib'd the Heavens but as they appear to the <HI>Eye.</HI> But when I re&s;olv'd to attempt the <HI>Con&s;lagration,</HI> I pre&s;ently di&s;cern'd, that the Horror of the Imagery would be wonderfully heigh|ten'd, by extending the De&s;ign to a De&s;cription and Di&s;&s;olution of the <HI>Planetary</HI> Sy&s;tems, in all the amiable Magnificence of our Modern <HI>A&s;tronomy.</HI> And, in this, I had the good Fortune to agree with, and receive &s;everal fine Hints from, the Ingenious Mr. <HI>Walter Bowman</HI> of St. <HI>Andrews,</HI> who, among a great many ex|cellent Qualifications, which he &s;uffers not to be half &s;o much known as they de|&s;erve to be, &s;hines, di&s;tingui&s;hably&punc; for his Skill in Sir <HI>I&s;aac Newton</HI>'s va&s;t Improvements. As to the <HI>Judgment</HI> it&s;elf, I thought it Nece&s;&s;ary, it &s;hould be as <HI>&s;hort,</HI> as could be &s;uitable to its Solemnity.</P>
<P>The Gentlemen, who have been copious in their <HI>Preparations, Embeli&s;hments,</HI> and <HI>De&s;criptions,</HI> on this dreadful Subject, have not <HI>felt</HI> it, as they ought. Their Means and their End, were too widely di&s;proportioned, and their Succe&s;s has been An&s;werable. They bring to my Remembrance the Accident, which befel <HI>Ja|cob,</HI> who put his Limbs out of Joynt by <HI>wre&s;tling</HI> with an <HI>Angel.</HI></P>
<P>When we let our Fancy loo&s;e, on this frightful Di&s;covery, we conceive an In|di&s;tinct and a&s;toni&s;hing Idea of &s;omething, horribly prodigious, and which is too mighty for our Gra&s;p. But it bur&s;ts from our very Approach, and <HI>overflows Humane Thought,</HI> when we would draw it into De&s;cription! <HI>Sittings, Hearings, Pleadings&punc; Confrontings, Examination of Witne&s;&s;es,</HI> and all &s;uch faint Images, as we
<PB N="4" REF="5">
can Copy from our Earthly Forms of Ju&s;tice, are infinitely too narrow for the unlimited Maje&s;ty of the <HI>Eternal.</HI> His Omni&s;cience di&s;dains <HI>Proofs;</HI> and a <HI>Sentence</HI> is the <HI>Judgment,</HI> which we mu&s;t expect from the <HI>Almighty!</HI> A Sen|tence! which the &s;peaking Con&s;cience of the Hearers &s;hall <HI>approve:</HI> Even while it condemns to an Eternal Puni&s;hment, that Self-convicting Guilt, which ju&s;tifies, to the <HI>Adjudg'd them&s;elves,</HI> the Rigour of the <HI>Judgment.</HI></P>
<CLOSER><DATELINE>March <HI>the</HI> <DATE>1&s;t. 1720/1.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SIGNED>A. HILL.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
